# Fetch Library Docs via Context7

Before implementing or modifying code that depends on an external library or API, use the Context7 MCP to fetch current documentation rather than relying on training data.

## When to fetch

- Integrating a new library feature (e.g. prompt caching, streaming, batch API)
- Hitting an unexpected API error or type mismatch
- Upgrading a dependency to a new major/minor version
- Uncertain whether a parameter, method, or pattern is still current

## How

1. Call `mcp_context7_resolve-library-id` with the library name (e.g. `anthropic sdk typescript`, `drizzle orm`)
2. Call `mcp_context7_get-library-docs` with the resolved ID and a topic query (e.g. `prompt caching`, `sqlite migrations`)
3. Use the returned docs as the source of truth for types, parameters, and usage patterns

## Key libraries in this project

| Library | Context7 search term |
|---------|---------------------|
| Anthropic Claude SDK | `anthropic sdk typescript` |
| Drizzle ORM | `drizzle orm` |
| Zod | `zod` |
| @stoqey/ib (IBKR) | `stoqey ib` |
| Biome | `biome` |

## Do NOT

- Guess API shapes from memory when docs are one MCP call away
- Assume training-data knowledge of SDK types is current — versions move fast
- Skip fetching when a TypeScript type error suggests the SDK has changed
